   <abstract >Although the Vietnam War officially ended on April 30, 1975, the destruction it yielded and the diaspora that followed continue to haunt those directly affected by it. Remembering trauma through storytelling has proven supportive of individual and shared healing, but how can such lived experiences, which remain at odds with established narratives, be legitimized, much less preserved? Despite renewed scholarly interest in the art of protest made in reaction to the Vietnam War, no publication has engaged with postwar artistic representations of this history. Also missing in the art historical scholarship is the study of an artwork informed by storytelling. My project combines a narratological approach with memory studies to examine how An-My Lê's Small Wars (1999 – 2002), Jessica Hines's My Brother's War (2006-2020), and Tiffany Chung's Remapping History: an autopsy of a battle, an excavation of a man's past (2015 – 18) reconstruct fragmented and secondary memories into photo-based, diaristic narratives. Through building on the scholarship of landscape, documentary, and vernacular photography, I demonstrate how each artist stylistically refers to these genres to give form to acts of remembering and the conditions of displacement, grief, and loss. What results from these narratives are gaps, which arguably speak to the voices and stories excluded from official narratives of the war. Not only do Small Wars, My Brother's War, and Remapping History attest to the transnational significance of photography as a medium where artistic traditions, geopolitical histories, and cultural heritages converge, but they also promote a more inclusive memory of the war that highlights the plurality of American history.</abstract>
